body:
Hi @qubvel 
I am glad that you find my contribution to `keras-applications` useful and I would be happy to help you. I am, however, not exactly sure how I can help you, since you already seem to have quite a nice implementation of EfficientNet. Could you provide me with more details?

@Callidior My model is not suited both for keras and tf.keras, I have two different branches for that. But your model written in keras applications style to work with both. If you want you can just paste your model code to https://github.com/qubvel/efficientnet/blob/feature/merging-keras-tf.keras/efficientnet/model.py (`feature/merging-keras-tf.keras` branch) and make a PR. I will do the rest. Or I can copy it by myself, if you are not against it, and mention you as author.

issue.title: EfficientNet implementation compatible to keras and tf.keras (resolves #39)

repository.name: efficientnet
repository.description: Implementation of EfficientNet model. Keras and TensorFlow Keras.

body: Okay, I created PR #42 with an exact copy of my code. Hope it helps!

Everything works ok for keras, but tf.keras throw an error in Dropout layer https://travis-ci.com/qubvel/efficientnet/jobs/218365138
@Callidior do you have any thoughts?

In my opinion, this is a bug in `tf.keras`. I compared the implementation of the Dropout layer with that of `keras` and found that `tf.keras` does not replace `None`-valued dimensions with the actual batch size. `keras` does this in [`keras.layers.Dropout._get_noise_shape`](https://github.com/keras-team/keras/blob/master/keras/layers/core.py#L110):

```python
def _get_noise_shape(self, inputs):
    if self.noise_shape is None:
        return self.noise_shape

    symbolic_shape = K.shape(inputs)
    noise_shape = [symbolic_shape[axis] if shape is None else shape
                   for axis, shape in enumerate(self.noise_shape)]
    return tuple(noise_shape)
```

`tf.keras` just leaves the dimension of the batch axis as `None`, which leads to the error.

A clean fix would be to derive a custom dropout layer compatible with both frameworks, which implements the correct behaviour:
```python
class Dropout(layers.Dropout):
    
    def _get_noise_shape(self, inputs):
        
        if self.noise_shape is None:
            return self.noise_shape

        symbolic_shape = backend.shape(inputs)
        noise_shape = [symbolic_shape[axis] if shape is None else shape
                       for axis, shape in enumerate(self.noise_shape)]
        return tuple(noise_shape)
```

But then, you need to include this layer in the `custom_objects` dictionary for de-serializing saved models.

A more hacky fix, which I didn't completely test, would be to replace `noise_shape=(None, 1, 1, 1)` in the model construction code with `noise_shape=(backend.shape(x)[0], 1, 1, 1)`, but I don't like this solution and suspect that it might lead to different errors at some point.

Thanks for clarification, I dont like that I have to shadow new Dropout class definition, because at first time `layers` module is None and I can not use inheritance from `layers.Layer`. But may be its a price for compatibility)
Are you going to make a bug report to `tensorflow`?

I also have included `swish` to global custom objects to make model deserializable. May be you also need to do it in your keras-applications PR?

I don't like any of these workarounds either and have filed a bug report at https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/issues/30946, but who knows how long it will take them to fix it.

Maybe the second "hack" I suggested might be a quick solution for you in the meantime.
Hack with `noise_shape=(backend.shape(x)[0], 1, 1, 1)` does not work, because object is not serializable, while defining a custom Dropout layer works fine. Thanks a lot :+1:

Hm, I somewhat expected that. Thanks for checking. :+1: 
But besides the custom Dropout layer, I don't see another way at the moment, unfortunately.

It was noted in the tensorflow issue that this bug has recently been fixed in https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/commit/ab2644e7178312fc9c89f90d7c8e61f73f7c1f64. But that commit does not seem to have made it into a release yet.

Thanks, will wait for release to update)
For now the work is done, thanks again for your help!

issue.title: Remove `FixedDropout`

repository.name: efficientnet
repository.description: Implementation of EfficientNet model. Keras and TensorFlow Keras.

issue.body: The `FixedDropout` (mentioned in https://github.com/qubvel/efficientnet/issues/39) was created to circumvent an issue in tensorflow.keras that has been fixed and merged (commit: https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/commit/ab2644e7178312fc9c89f90d7c8e61f73f7c1f64) since. I think the `FixedDropout` class should be removed.
